One, two!
One, two, three, four!

01:37.208 --> 01:41.041
Juan always said he didn't believe
anything from History class.

01:41.208 --> 01:43.333
Or books, for that matter.

01:43.458 --> 01:47.416
How could they be so sure
what Hernan Cortes thought...

01:47.791 --> 01:50.625
...or Montezuma,
or Alexander the Great?

01:50.916 --> 01:53.041
He said it was all made up.

01:54.250 --> 01:57.250
He said no one could know
why someone did what they did...

01:57.583 --> 01:59.500
...except for the person
who did it.

01:59.666 --> 02:01.791
And more often than not,
not even them.

02:02.041 --> 02:03.041
Water.

02:03.333 --> 02:05.791
Skies crisscrossed by clouds.

02:06.125 --> 02:08.249
Silent mountains.

02:08.499 --> 02:11.041
Elements controlled by Tlaloc.

02:12.458 --> 02:18.166
For centuries, the 300 A.D. monolith
slumbered in a ravine.

02:18.750 --> 02:21.166
Juan told me about the time
when some engineers...

02:21.416 --> 02:24.833
...took the god Tlaloc
away from his home.

02:25.583 --> 02:30.708
People were angry and sad,
but they took him anyway.

02:31.166 --> 02:34.250
Without asking for permission
or forgiveness.

02:36.458 --> 02:40.833
On the huge platform
powered by 860 hp...

02:41.083 --> 02:44.541
...the god's transportation
took place over two stages.

02:44.833 --> 02:48.791
From the shores of Texcoco Lake
to the Chapultepec Forest.

02:49.208 --> 02:54.833
Power and telephone cables
had to be removed along the way.

02:56.250 --> 02:58.208
And all because
they had to fill...

02:58.291 --> 03:01.833
...the new anthropology museum
with old things.

03:07.375 --> 03:09.291
The city was lit up...

03:09.583 --> 03:13.291
...as Tlaloc traversed it
in his immortal slumber.

03:13.708 --> 03:16.833
Witnessing the centuries-old
journey of the god...

03:17.083 --> 03:22.625
...hundreds of thousands
watched in awe and curiosity.

03:28.250 --> 03:31.166
- Photo!
- Stop it, stop.

03:31.500 --> 03:33.416
- Get down.
- Oh, sweetie.

03:33.833 --> 03:36.333
Soon after the museum opened,
Juan's father...

03:36.416 --> 03:39.583
...took Juan to see Tlaloc
and told him about the plunder.

03:39.916 --> 03:42.875
- Honey, please smile.
- I'm smiling.

03:43.625 --> 03:45.666
Juan was five years old.

03:47.458 --> 03:51.250
- Smile, Juan! Show your teeth!
- He never forgot the story.

03:53.291 --> 03:57.750
"Death is our eternal companion"

03:59.291 --> 04:02.458
"Always to our left"

04:02.791 --> 04:07.375
"An arm's distance away"

04:20.583 --> 04:23.750
The first time I visited the museum,
back in eighth grade...

04:23.833 --> 04:27.166
...I had to copy the captions
next to the pieces...

04:27.625 --> 04:31.541
...and get my notebook stamped
to prove I had been there.

04:32.000 --> 04:35.583
I heard stories about
the creation, and wars...

04:35.833 --> 04:38.458
...and about the things
that used to be here.

04:38.750 --> 04:44.458
"It whispers in your ear
You felt its icy touch"

04:45.458 --> 04:51.166
"The way you felt it today"

04:52.458 --> 04:53.958
But I don't remember
any of it.

04:55.791 --> 05:02.750
"It has always been
Watching over you"

05:06.583 --> 05:10.125
"And it always will"

05:14.583 --> 05:16.416
Next piece, please.

05:21.708 --> 05:23.083
Turn it off.

05:26.750 --> 05:28.041
Turn it off.

05:28.750 --> 05:29.958
Juan.

05:30.458 --> 05:31.666
Juan!

05:32.250 --> 05:33.958
- Turn off the light!
- Sorry, sorry.

05:34.208 --> 05:36.333
The year of the earthquake,
Juan spent the summer...

05:36.583 --> 05:38.958
...working at the museum
to pay for his weed.

05:39.500 --> 05:42.125
Every day for three months
they took photographs...

05:42.333 --> 05:45.125
...of each object
at the Maya room.

05:45.666 --> 05:48.250
And it seemed
they'd never finish.

05:50.833 --> 05:53.125
Rotate it counterclockwise,
please.

05:55.250 --> 05:57.750
What are you doing?
No touching without gloves!

05:58.000 --> 06:01.875
Juan, if you touch a piece again,
I'm sending you home.

06:05.541 --> 06:09.208
Juan used to say it was impossible
to know how things start...

06:09.500 --> 06:12.208
...we can only know
how they end...

06:12.541 --> 06:14.166
...once they've ended.

06:14.708 --> 06:19.041
I don't know if those photos
were the beginning of it all.

06:21.541 --> 06:23.333
I don't know.

06:25.250 --> 06:27.500
Where does an idea begin?

06:32.666 --> 06:34.208
Who can tell?

